ns and seven policy advisors around the central development issues of social protection, public health, public education and natural resource management. How did certain ideas, and not others, gain traction in shaping particular policy responses? How did the content and effectiveness of these responses vary across different countries, and indeed within them? Achieving this is not merely a matter of seeking to 'know more' about specific times, places and issues, but recognising the distinctive ways in which historians rigorously assemble, analyse and interpret diverse forms of evidence. This book will appeal to students and scholars in development studies, history, international relations, politics and geography as well as policy makers and those working for or studying NGOs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  acolonial education.  adevelopmental institution.  aindigenous development policy.  amass literacy.  amodern-day China.  anineteenth-century Africa.  anineteenth-century India.  aprofessional historians.  apublic education.  apublic health.  aresource curse hypothesis.  asanitation.  asocial security.1 aAmrith, Sunil S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayly, C. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayly, C.A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBreckenridge, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall-Mathews, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanbur, Ravi, econtributor.4ctb4http